            "I've found comprehensive research on NBA game outcome prediction using machine learning with rolling averages. Here are the key findings:\n\n## Feature Engineering with Rolling Averages\n\nResearch shows that comprehensive feature sets for NBA predictions include traditional basic statistics along with rolling averages that reflect recent form (e.g., over the last 5 and 10 games), and metrics quantifying relative team advantages in a given matchup.\n\nMany studies commonly use the average of the last 10 games as a basis for this feature, though the number of games can be varied to see what impact they have on the algorithm.\n\n## Importance of Rolling Averages\n\nRolling averages are important in improving accuracy as they help smooth out noisy data, identify long-term trends, and handle seasonal or cyclical patterns. By reducing short-term fluctuations, rolling averages provide a more stable estimate or prediction, enabling a clearer understanding of underlying trends and patterns\u2014valuable for sports analytics where accuracy is crucial.\n\n## Key Predictive Features\n\nKey performance indicators such as field goal percentage, defensive rebounds, and turnovers are consistently related to game outcomes at all times during the game. In the first half of games, assists are a key indicator, while in the second half, offensive rebounds and three-point shooting percentage are key indicators affecting outcomes.\n\n## Model Performance\n\nThe XGBoost model demonstrated superior predictive capability on an independent test set, achieving an accuracy of 73.6%."
