            "I've found comprehensive research on NBA prediction using feature engineering with rolling windows and opponent-adjusted statistics. Here are the key findings:\n\n## Rolling Window Statistics\n\nModels typically ingest more than 50 variables for every game, including rolling team statistics over the last 5, 10, and 20 games, as well as opponent defensive stats measured through the Four Factors on defense (eFG% allowed, turnovers forced, offensive rebounds conceded, and free throws allowed).\n\nAdvanced feature engineering includes 3-, 5-, 7-, and 10-game-lag averages for player performance metrics.\n\n## Opponent-Adjusted Statistics\n\nOpponent defensive metrics are essential as they measure not what the team does on offense, but what it prevents opponents from doing. A team with low opponent eFG percentage has an elite defense.\n\nEach player's opponent dataset is created based on their future matchup using the team's dataset, then joined with their corresponding team's performance and the next opponent's performance data.\n\n## Matchup Features\n\nThe Home_Win_Prob_Combined provides a nuanced prediction that balances rolling average team performance with historical matchups. Matchup interaction features include pace_matchup (interaction of both teams' pace profiles), net_rtg_diff (Net Rating gap), and pace_diff (style asymmetry).\n\n## Model Performance\n\nFinal models have reported average accuracy around 65.1%, meaning they can predict NBA game outcomes about 65% of the time, with more sophisticated rolling learning approaches achieving accuracy of 70.75%."
